  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime and drug trafficking\n- Initial focus on tracking criminal proceeds and financial transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (United States) - First comprehensive anti-money laundering legislation\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act - Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established internationally\n\n3. International Conventions\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Drug Trafficking\n- 2000 UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Established global standards for criminalizing money laundering\n\n4. Expanded Legal Frameworks\n- Progressively broader definitions of financial crimes\n- Enhanced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Increased international cooperation and information sharing\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments\n- Patriot Act substantially expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Greater focus on terrorist financing prevention\n- More stringent Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Increased global regulatory collaboration\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
